00:12:31,133 --> 00:12:34,068
Just 'cause the guy doesn't
publish fancy clinical trials,

228
00:12:34,170 --> 00:12:38,339
or take on flashy surgeries, or have
creepy perfect hair, he's less of a man?

229
00:12:38,441 --> 00:12:39,791
Kinda.

230
00:12:50,403 --> 00:12:52,086
How'd it go with the lawyers?

231
00:12:52,188 --> 00:12:54,300
They told me my death rate.

232
00:12:54,324 --> 00:12:57,091
These are the people I saved.

233
00:12:58,395 --> 00:13:00,515
These are the people I killed.

234
00:13:02,832 --> 00:13:07,485
Most of those were terminal when they
came to you, you were their last chance.

235
00:13:07,587 --> 00:13:11,289
And you take on impossible
cases. Look at the clinical trial.

236
00:13:11,391 --> 00:13:13,324
There's so many people.

237
00:13:13,426 --> 00:13:16,644
More than Dahmer,
Manson and Bundy combined.

238
00:13:16,746 --> 00:13:19,146
You're not looking
at the big picture.

239
00:13:22,335 --> 00:13:25,102
This is the big picture.

240
00:13:29,008 --> 00:13:30,908
Shepherd! Thank God you're back.

241
00:13:31,010 --> 00:13:33,978
- Can you swing
two brain biopsies?
- I'm not operating.

242
00:13:34,080 --> 00:13:36,914
I know you've got a big lawsuit
breathing down your neck,

243
00:13:37,016 --> 00:13:39,066
I know you lost a patient,
but I need you back,

244
00:13:39,186 --> 00:13:41,947
- doing the job
I hired you to do.
- I am not operating.

245
00:13:42,021 --> 00:13:44,955
I'm not asking, I'm
telling as Chief Surgeon,

246
00:13:45,058 --> 00:13:48,193
if you don't get back into
that OR today, Shepherd...

247
00:13:55,535 --> 00:13:57,835
And he just walked out.
Without saying a word.

248
00:13:57,937 --> 00:14:01,121
Hunt won't look at me since he
went all <i>Apocalypse Now</i> this morning.

249
00:14:01,223 --> 00:14:05,009
Had to get scalpel happy in that
patient's brain and can't face it.

250
00:14:05,111 --> 00:14:07,839
He thinks I'm this wilting
flower. I'm the strong one.

251
00:14:07,863 --> 00:14:10,559
- I'm the strong one.
- If I had that
stomach cancer gene?

252
00:14:10,583 --> 00:14:13,901
I'd get that gastrectomy. I
face things, I don't walk away.

253
00:14:14,003 --> 00:14:16,237
Derek walks away. Maybe
walking away is the answer.

254
00:14:16,339 --> 00:14:19,607
It's not emotional, it's science.
Have a problem, don't ignore it.

255
00:14:19,709 --> 00:14:22,743
If you have to pee, and you
ignore it, it does go away.

256
00:14:22,845 --> 00:14:25,157
You guys are hilarious!

257
00:14:25,181 --> 00:14:29,133
Do you even know what she
just said? Or what she just said?

258
00:14:29,235 --> 00:14:31,869
I see you guys in 50
years in a nursing home,

259
00:14:31,971 --> 00:14:36,574
just talking at each other with
your hearing aids off. Hi-larious.

260
00:14:37,843 --> 00:14:40,411
Oh! I love lunch.

261
00:14:50,774 --> 00:14:52,423
What the hell?

262
00:14:53,626 --> 00:14:55,209
Beth?

263
00:14:56,446 --> 00:14:58,245
Code blue!

264
00:15:00,984 --> 00:15:03,862
After I take out the
stomach I'll do what, Yang?

265
00:15:03,886 --> 00:15:08,689
- Sew the esophageal
anastomosis.
- Or the other option is, Grey?

266
00:15:08,791 --> 00:15:10,724
You could staple
the anastomosis.

267
00:15:10,826 --> 00:15:12,654
Now why would I want to do that?

268
00:15:12,678 --> 00:15:14,896
Fistula rates can be
higher when you hand sew.

269
00:15:14,998 --> 00:15:19,066
You might say that using the
old stapler is sort of my specialty.

270
00:15:19,168 --> 00:15:24,088
Thought your specialty was baby-sitting.
I'm sure you'd rather be doing that.

271
00:15:24,190 --> 00:15:26,173
Frankly, sir, I feel like I am.

272
00:15:26,275 --> 00:15:29,460
Excuse me, sir, I think
you should feel this.

273
00:15:29,562 --> 00:15:31,278
Right here.

274
00:15:36,836 --> 00:15:39,853
Tell me that's not
what I think it is.

275
00:15:43,226 --> 00:15:44,858
Wait, I think I got it.

276
00:15:44,960 --> 00:15:47,545
Liver enzymes are normal,
cardiac workup's negative...

277
00:15:47,647 --> 00:15:50,014
- If LDH is a false positive...
- It's a trick question.

278
00:15:50,116 --> 00:15:53,367
- What?
- She's fine. Patient X is fine.

279
00:15:53,469 --> 00:15:56,670
- She's not fine.
- Her SED rate
is slightly elevated.

280
00:15:56,773 --> 00:16:00,591
- Did we check for
autoimmune disease?
- ANA and CRP were negative.

281
00:16:00,693 --> 00:16:04,895
At worst, she's got an anxiety
disorder. The girl is totally fine.

282
00:16:05,432 --> 00:16:07,949
She is not fine!

283
00:16:09,152 --> 00:16:10,969
She had hallucinations.

284
00:16:11,071 --> 00:16:16,273
She had visual, auditory
and tactile hallucinations

285
00:16:16,376 --> 00:16:18,893
about her dead fiancé.

286
00:16:18,995 --> 00:16:23,147
She thought she could
talk to him and touch him.

287
00:16:23,249 --> 00:16:25,549
She is not fine.

288
00:16:25,651 --> 00:16:27,952
She is not fine.

289
00:16:31,357 --> 00:16:33,808
You're missing something.

290
00:16:33,910 --> 00:16:38,545
You're not looking in the right place.
Go back, figure out what you're missing.

291
00:16:42,602 --> 00:16:44,935
She has it? Trish has cancer?

292
00:16:45,037 --> 00:16:49,806
The cancer was stage one. We got to it
so early, the gastrectomy was curative.

293
00:16:49,909 --> 00:16:51,625
She had her endoscopy
a few months ago.

294
00:16:51,727 --> 00:16:54,429
It was an aggressive
cancer that grew quickly.

295
00:16:54,531 --> 00:16:58,633
- The fact we took
her stomach today...
- It saved your sister's life.

296
00:17:01,971 --> 00:17:04,099
The reason Trish
decides everything,

297
00:17:04,123 --> 00:17:06,958
Thanksgiving,
dinners, vacations...

298
00:17:07,060 --> 00:17:09,738
She's the only one left who
knows how to cook a turkey, Mike.

299
00:17:09,762 --> 00:17:13,213
She's the only one left
who likes planning vacations,

300
00:17:13,315 --> 00:17:16,184
who ever remembers to
make dinner reservations.

301
00:17:16,286 --> 00:17:20,587
She's in charge of us
because everyone else is dead.

302
00:17:21,124 --> 00:17:23,273
I want it. Now.

303
00:17:23,375 --> 00:17:25,443
I want the surgery right now.

304
00:17:32,051 --> 00:17:34,885
Why is she coding when she
seizes? It doesn't make sense.

305
00:17:34,987 --> 00:17:37,099
Not this young. Her
heart should be fine.

306
00:17:37,123 --> 00:17:40,541
Beth coded before her seizure not
during. I saw her heart go into v-fib.

307
00:17:40,643 --> 00:17:44,178
- She's 17 with
no heart history, Karev.
- I saw it on the monitor.

308
00:17:44,280 --> 00:17:48,348
You think you saw it on the monitor.
Seizures are chaotic. Doctors panic...

309
00:17:48,450 --> 00:17:50,017
I didn't panic. I
know what I saw.

310
00:17:50,136 --> 00:17:51,864
You suggesting
I tell her parents

311
00:17:51,888 --> 00:17:54,038
she's been wrongly
treated for six years?

312
00:17:54,140 --> 00:17:56,390
We should run a cardiac
workup with an EP study.

313
00:17:56,492 --> 00:18:01,195
You want me to deliberately shock a
perfectly healthy heart? Absolutely not!

314
00:18:03,532 --> 00:18:06,050
- Dr. Hunt?
- If right, it'd explain
the coding.

315
00:18:06,152 --> 00:18:09,454
- If he's wrong,
it will kill her!
- I'm not wrong!

316
00:18:16,195 --> 00:18:18,562
Then it's your call, Karev.

317
00:18:28,207 --> 00:18:29,706
Maybe Cristina's right.

318
00:18:29,808 --> 00:18:32,409
Maybe trying to teach
the interns is pointless.

319
00:18:32,512 --> 00:18:35,646
Don't listen to Cristina. She
thinks because you'd rather teach

320
00:18:35,748 --> 00:18:38,516
than take out a gallbladder,
that you're the new me.

321
00:18:39,936 --> 00:18:44,221
- O'Malley the sequel.
- O'Malley 2.0.

322
00:18:48,261 --> 00:18:51,511
You read more journals
and do more research

323
00:18:51,614 --> 00:18:55,866
and log more hours in the skills
lab than any other resident here.

324
00:18:55,968 --> 00:18:58,280
You never give up trying
to be a better doctor.

325
00:18:58,304 --> 00:19:02,039
And you don't step
on other people to do it.

326
00:19:02,141 --> 00:19:04,542
I would be lucky
to be the new you.

327
00:19:10,700 --> 00:19:14,218
You gonna tell me
about Patient X?

328
00:19:14,320 --> 00:19:17,254
- I know what we missed.
- I gotta go, George.

329
00:19:17,357 --> 00:19:20,057
She had enlarged lymph
nodes, but it's not mono.

330
00:19:20,159 --> 00:19:22,059
What if we missed a
malignancy in her brain?

331
00:19:22,161 --> 00:19:24,895
- You ruled that out
with the CT.
- That was a mistake.

332
00:19:24,997 --> 00:19:27,748
I'd like an MRI with contrast,
maybe biopsy a lymph node.

333
00:19:27,850 --> 00:19:30,401
Whatever's wrong,
it's already in her brain.

334
00:19:30,503 --> 00:19:33,303
Yeah.

335
00:19:33,406 --> 00:19:35,022
Clamp's going in.

336
00:19:35,124 --> 00:19:36,869
I don't feel any masses.

337
00:19:36,893 --> 00:19:38,158
2-O vicryl please.

338
00:19:38,260 --> 00:19:39,844
Sir, if I may one more time,

339
00:19:39,946 --> 00:19:41,912
I think stapling would
be a better choice.

340
00:19:42,014 --> 00:19:45,649
Dr. Bailey, you no longer wish
to be a surgeon in this hospital.

341
00:19:45,751 --> 00:19:47,813
So leave the technical
calls up to me.

342
00:19:47,837 --> 00:19:50,655
I was expressing my opinion
what would be best for my patient.

343
00:19:50,757 --> 00:19:54,658
You don't get an opinion! This is
my patient because it's my hospital.

344
00:19:54,760 --> 00:19:57,989
When it's your hospital you
make decisions, but until then,

345
00:19:58,013 --> 00:20:02,132
this is my hospital and I want
all of you people to do what I say!

346
00:20:07,523 --> 00:20:09,223
Yes, sir.

347
00:20:09,325 --> 00:20:11,625
2-O vicryl, please.

348
00:20:20,770 --> 00:20:25,256
You're gonna be OK.
You're in really good hands.

349
00:20:32,614 --> 00:20:36,249
I'm going to ask you
one more time, Karev.

350
00:20:36,351 --> 00:20:38,285
Are you sure about this?

351
00:20:38,788 --> 00:20:40,437
Yeah.

352
00:20:42,425 --> 00:20:44,124
Then you're on crash cart.

353
00:20:44,226 --> 00:20:46,109
If you're wrong...

354
00:20:47,096 --> 00:20:48,812
be ready to use it.

355
00:21:03,463 --> 00:21:05,563
Your path report
came back clear,

356
00:21:05,665 --> 00:21:09,177
there were no cancerous cells in
your stomach. How's your pain?

357
00:21:09,201 --> 00:21:12,552
The wound hurts a
little... not too bad, right?

358
00:21:12,654 --> 00:21:14,388
Yeah.

359
00:21:17,559 --> 00:21:20,759
Don't you remember how much
pain Mom was in at the end?

360
00:21:20,830 --> 00:21:22,362
No.

361
00:21:22,481 --> 00:21:24,810
You used to help me wet
her lips with an ice cube.

362
00:21:24,834 --> 00:21:27,334
It was awful. She
couldn't even drink.

363
00:21:27,436 --> 00:21:30,137
She had so many
tubes everywhere.

364
00:21:30,239 --> 00:21:34,574
I don't remember. I was two
years old when Mom died.

365
00:21:34,676 --> 00:21:37,611
The only reason I know
it was sad and horrible

366
00:21:37,730 --> 00:21:40,647
is because you
tell me all the time.

367
00:21:41,650 --> 00:21:44,568
I don't have nightmares
about funerals.

368
00:21:44,670 --> 00:21:49,256
I don't freak out and think it's cancer
every time I have indigestion. You do.

369
00:21:49,358 --> 00:21:52,259
- Mike...
- This is your fear.

370
00:21:52,862 --> 00:21:54,695
It's not mine.

371
00:21:54,797 --> 00:21:58,799
So just let me decide
when I'm scared.

372
00:22:03,889 --> 00:22:06,824
- Let's take the pace
down to 300.
- Vitals are still stable.

373
00:22:06,926 --> 00:22:10,406
This is pointless. The study is
showing no sign of arrhythmia.

374
00:22:11,463 --> 00:22:14,465
- Wait. She's in v-tach.
- Let's pace her
out of it at 330.

375
00:22:14,567 --> 00:22:16,750
- BP's down to 60 over 10.
- 340. Damn it.

376
00:22:16,852 --> 00:22:18,902
Karev, get in there, now.

377
00:22:19,004 --> 00:22:21,939
Wait, hold the shock.

378
00:22:30,782 --> 00:22:32,416
She's coming out of it.

379
00:22:32,518 --> 00:22:36,078
This could be ARVC. The right
ventricle's causing arrhythmia.

380
00:22:36,105 --> 00:22:39,873
- The brain doesn't get oxygen.
- And she seizes. Oh, my God.

381
00:22:43,896 --> 00:22:46,347
Karev, you just
saved this girl's life.

382
00:22:58,461 --> 00:23:02,228
It's OK. It's OK, just breathe.

383
00:23:03,265 --> 00:23:04,976
Put the paddles
down and breathe.

384
00:23:05,000 --> 00:23:08,469
It's OK... it's OK.

385
00:23:20,516 --> 00:23:22,733
Well, it wasn't easy.

386
00:23:22,835 --> 00:23:27,003
Not only did I push through my hare
lip reconstruction and a tympanoplasty,

387
00:23:27,105 --> 00:23:32,143
but I pulled out a burn graft so
beautiful it could bring a man to tears.

388
00:23:36,833 --> 00:23:38,532
Chief?

389
00:23:38,634 --> 00:23:41,151
You haven't heard from
Shepherd, have you?

390
00:23:44,457 --> 00:23:47,458
No, sir. I haven't.

391
00:23:48,961 --> 00:23:54,681
Sir, I have tried to let it
go, I know it's not personal,

392
00:23:54,783 --> 00:23:56,950
I understand it's
very hard for you,

393
00:23:57,052 --> 00:24:00,303
I understand you're under
a great deal of pressure,

394
00:24:00,405 --> 00:24:03,674
but the way you
yelled at me in the OR,

395
00:24:03,776 --> 00:24:06,343
today, in front of my residents?

396
00:24:06,445 --> 00:24:09,796
Not OK, sir. Not OK at all.

397
00:24:09,898 --> 00:24:15,185
Now you and me, we're going to have
to find a way to work together so you...

398
00:24:16,522 --> 00:24:18,288
Not talking to me now?

399
00:24:19,342 --> 00:24:20,607
Oh! Well...

400
00:24:20,709 --> 00:24:24,979
That's just real mature, sir.

401
00:24:26,315 --> 00:24:28,515
Real mature.

402
00:24:31,571 --> 00:24:33,570
We have a diagnosis.

403
00:24:36,041 --> 00:24:37,374
Go ahead, Dr. Grey.

404
00:24:37,476 --> 00:24:42,146
Patient X. An elevated
LDH was our only clue.

405
00:24:42,248 --> 00:24:46,400
We found out she had enlarged lymph
nodes and a mole, which was biopsied.

406
00:24:46,501 --> 00:24:51,405
Meanwhile, this MRI with contrast
showed a met on her right temporal lobe.

407
00:24:51,507 --> 00:24:54,024
The biopsy revealed
dividing cells.

408
00:24:54,126 --> 00:24:56,459
That, coupled with
further staging tests,

409
00:24:56,562 --> 00:24:59,797
led to our final diagnosis
of metastatic melanoma

410
00:24:59,899 --> 00:25:02,866
with mets to the
liver, skin, and brain.

411
00:25:08,291 --> 00:25:12,876
- Your prognosis?
- With chemo
and radiation...

412
00:25:12,978 --> 00:25:15,696
- a few months.
- At best. The girl's toast.

413
00:25:15,798 --> 00:25:17,993
Survival rate's five percent.

414
00:25:18,017 --> 00:25:20,817
If I were her I'd go on
a really good vacation.

415
00:25:28,310 --> 00:25:30,460
Good job, everybody.

416
00:25:31,330 --> 00:25:33,229
That's it?

417
00:25:33,331 --> 00:25:36,650
- The last contest,
we got a prize.
- What's our prize?

418
00:25:39,054 --> 00:25:44,658
You think every time you hand
someone a death sentence there's a prize?

419
00:25:46,478 --> 00:25:50,614
The prize is, you didn't
screw it up this time.

420
00:25:50,716 --> 00:25:53,651
The prize is, you people
actually did something right.

421
00:25:53,753 --> 00:25:58,956
The prize is, you were doctors today!
You are doctors. That is the prize.

422
00:26:14,873 --> 00:26:19,193
- Adele, what are you
doing here?
- Conference room, Richard. Now.

423
00:26:20,796 --> 00:26:23,330
You too, Miranda. Let's go.

424
00:26:30,522 --> 00:26:34,741
It's a pacemaker. It's gonna
regulate your abnormal arrhythmias,

425
00:26:34,843 --> 00:26:38,011
so you won't have
any more seizures.

426
00:26:38,113 --> 00:26:42,549
So... I'm not sick anymore?

427
00:26:42,651 --> 00:26:43,850
A wrestler fixed me.

428
00:26:43,970 --> 00:26:46,253
Not exactly. You have
a serious heart condition,

429
00:26:46,355 --> 00:26:48,667
we're gonna set you
up with a cardiologist...

430
00:26:48,691 --> 00:26:51,775
But no one has to know. I
won't be frothing at the mouth,

431
00:26:51,877 --> 00:26:54,461
I don't have to wear
a bracelet to school.

432
00:26:54,563 --> 00:26:58,999
- I can cover this with a shirt.
- Yeah. That's something.

433
00:26:59,101 --> 00:27:00,534
It's everything.

434
00:27:00,636 --> 00:27:03,904
Once people see you as sick,
they don't see anything else.

435
00:27:06,825 --> 00:27:09,926
Mr. Bimm just called.
We didn't get a trophy.

436
00:27:11,230 --> 00:27:12,830
There's next season.

437
00:27:12,932 --> 00:27:16,344
Yeah, we were thinking, maybe
you should try out for choir or debate.

438
00:27:16,368 --> 00:27:21,905
Something requiring less movement.
We're just worried for your safety.

439
00:27:22,007 --> 00:27:26,626
You don't have to be. We
fixed her. Epileptic bone.

440
00:27:26,728 --> 00:27:27,906
What?

441
00:27:27,930 --> 00:27:29,791
There's no such thing
as an epileptic bone.

442
00:27:29,815 --> 00:27:31,080
Are you a doctor?

443
00:27:34,202 --> 00:27:37,170
So she's like...
totally normal now?

444
00:27:37,273 --> 00:27:41,241
Dude, none of you are normal.
You're freaking band nerds.

445
00:27:48,867 --> 00:27:51,552
Of all the petty,
ridiculous, infantile...

446
00:27:51,654 --> 00:27:53,503
Are you running a
hospital or a playground?

447
00:27:53,605 --> 00:27:57,374
- Adele, I will not be
spoken to...
- Hospital or playground?!

448
00:27:59,861 --> 00:28:02,062
- Hospital.
- Then start acting like

449
00:28:02,164 --> 00:28:06,750
the chief of a hospital and
apologize to that woman. Right now.

450
00:28:08,153 --> 00:28:10,704
- Sorry.
- You call that an apology!?

451
00:28:10,806 --> 00:28:13,691
Now you better not leave this
room until you work this out.

452
00:28:13,793 --> 00:28:17,277
If I have to drag myself here
through rush hour traffic again

453
00:28:17,379 --> 00:28:21,298
- to police this damn
jungle gym...
- Adele, you've made your point.

454
00:28:23,335 --> 00:28:26,119
And you wipe that smile off
your face. You're no better.

455
00:28:26,221 --> 00:28:29,139
Tattling on a man to his wife.

456
00:28:31,376 --> 00:28:34,211
When you have your stomach
out, you can't eat sugar.

457
00:28:34,313 --> 00:28:38,365
If he's doing this because he doesn't
want to give up damn jelly beans...

458
00:28:38,467 --> 00:28:40,534
- It's more than that.
- Or football

459
00:28:40,636 --> 00:28:43,603
or girls or snowboarding,
whatever, it doesn't matter.

460
00:28:43,705 --> 00:28:45,099
Not compared to the alternative.

461
00:28:45,123 --> 00:28:46,951
We'll be as vigilant as we can.

462
00:28:46,975 --> 00:28:50,194
- Use every screening
tool available.
- That won't be necessary.

463
00:28:50,296 --> 00:28:53,864
Mikey's gonna have the
surgery. Maybe not today,

464
00:28:53,966 --> 00:28:57,184
but I'm gonna be on him like glue,
to my dying breath, until he does.

465
00:28:57,286 --> 00:29:00,053
And if he just wants
to be left alone?

466
00:29:00,155 --> 00:29:03,390
You don't leave the people
you love alone, Dr. Grey.

467
00:29:03,492 --> 00:29:06,993
That idiot may not know it, but my
fear is what's going to save his life.

468
00:29:10,315 --> 00:29:11,931
<i>♪ Hold on ♪</i>

469
00:29:15,437 --> 00:29:19,423
I learned a lot, diagnosing a
patient from beginning to end.

470
00:29:19,525 --> 00:29:23,159
So... thank you for teaching us.

471
00:29:26,248 --> 00:29:27,947
What would you say?

472
00:29:30,618 --> 00:29:34,521
To Patient X. How would
you break the news?

473
00:29:35,941 --> 00:29:37,073
Um...

474
00:29:37,176 --> 00:29:39,909
I would say that
I was very sorry

475
00:29:40,012 --> 00:29:44,698
and that there were
support groups...

476
00:29:44,800 --> 00:29:49,285
I don't know. What do you say
to somebody who's going to...

477
00:29:50,705 --> 00:29:53,606
You say they have a choice.

478
00:29:54,526 --> 00:29:56,376
They can run away
and hide from it,

479
00:29:56,478 --> 00:29:58,444
or they can face it.

480
00:29:58,546 --> 00:30:00,613
You say to be around
people who love them,

481
00:30:00,715 --> 00:30:04,034
it's gonna be the toughest fight of
their life, no one should do it alone.

482
00:30:04,136 --> 00:30:06,820
And then you give them the odds,

483
00:30:06,922 --> 00:30:11,508
and even though a five percent survival
rate is bad, it's really bad, you say...

484
00:30:15,047 --> 00:30:19,282
- You say...
- Screw the odds.

485
00:30:19,384 --> 00:30:22,051
People die of the hiccups.

486
00:30:22,153 --> 00:30:24,065
My mother died of the hiccups.

487
00:30:24,089 --> 00:30:28,574
Survival rate for that
is, what, 100 percent?

488
00:30:28,694 --> 00:30:32,428
The odds are that she
should be alive right now.

489
00:30:32,531 --> 00:30:35,699
The odds are that
the odds mean crap.

490
00:30:37,002 --> 00:30:40,520
So people should face
it and they should fight.

491
00:30:43,809 --> 00:30:46,143
Maybe not those words.

492
00:30:47,228 --> 00:30:51,697
No... exactly those words.

493
00:30:54,703 --> 00:30:56,970
Thank you, Dr. Grey.

494
00:31:01,426 --> 00:31:02,725
How's she doing?

495
00:31:02,827 --> 00:31:05,395
- Uh, she's stable.
- Hmm.

496
00:31:06,281 --> 00:31:07,413
You did a hell of a job.

497
00:31:07,516 --> 00:31:08,877
The chief's gonna hear about it.

498
00:31:08,901 --> 00:31:11,501
Pretty impressive
for a resident.

499
00:31:11,603 --> 00:31:14,699
Fix that attitude, you could
be the future of this hospital,

500
00:31:14,723 --> 00:31:18,942
the one to watch. You go, Karev!

501
00:31:25,918 --> 00:31:27,383
Iz!

502
00:31:28,887 --> 00:31:31,432
Hunt's letting me do the distal
anastomosis on his fem-pop.

503
00:31:31,456 --> 00:31:33,640
- That's awesome.
- It's crazy.

504
00:31:33,742 --> 00:31:38,762
They told me I could be the future
of this hospital, the resident to watch.

505
00:31:38,847 --> 00:31:41,447
I mean, I'm not the
kind of guy who...

506
00:31:41,550 --> 00:31:44,184
I don't rise, OK? I
sink to the bottom.

507
00:31:44,303 --> 00:31:47,487
And now I'm getting
all this... this respect.

508
00:31:47,589 --> 00:31:52,325
And... And you... you gotta stop
wasting your time with this Patient X crap.

509
00:31:52,444 --> 00:31:54,845
- Alex...
- I know you like teaching,

510
00:31:54,947 --> 00:31:59,515
but you need to start treating
real patients with real surgeries

511
00:31:59,618 --> 00:32:03,086
because once they see you
as weak, it's over, and Iz...

512
00:32:03,188 --> 00:32:04,982
you could be a great surgeon.

513
00:32:05,006 --> 00:32:07,741
We could be great together.

514
00:32:07,843 --> 00:32:10,677
You just, you gotta
stop screwing around.

515
00:32:10,779 --> 00:32:15,398
I don't wanna be the future of this
hospital if you're not with me. OK?

516
00:32:16,784 --> 00:32:18,485
OK.

517
00:32:21,823 --> 00:32:23,924
- Alex!
- What?

518
00:32:27,512 --> 00:32:31,180
<i>♪ 'Cause I remember
what we said ♪</i>

519
00:32:31,282 --> 00:32:34,818
<i>♪ As we lay down to bed ♪</i>

520
00:32:34,920 --> 00:32:40,407
<i>♪ We'll be back as
soon as we make ♪</i>

521
00:32:40,509 --> 00:32:43,293
<i>♪ History ♪</i>

522
00:32:52,204 --> 00:32:55,071
- You told Adele on me?
- You stopped speaking to me.

523
00:32:55,173 --> 00:32:57,757
That didn't exactly
leave me many options.

524
00:32:57,859 --> 00:33:02,528
Would you have reacted like this
if I left general surgery for neuro?

525
00:33:02,631 --> 00:33:04,764
- Or cardio?
- I don't follow.

526
00:33:04,866 --> 00:33:07,884
Is it because you regard
peds as a soft specialty,

527
00:33:07,986 --> 00:33:09,285
is that what's bothering you?

528
00:33:09,387 --> 00:33:12,088
- That's ridiculous.
- Maybe. But...

529
00:33:12,190 --> 00:33:15,442
It seems that every time I do
something you perceive as "soft,"

530
00:33:15,544 --> 00:33:19,129
like having a baby, taking
some time off to see my baby,

531
00:33:19,231 --> 00:33:23,233
specializing in
babies... I'm dead to you.

532
00:33:23,318 --> 00:33:25,935
- Wanna know what I think?
- Not particularly.

533
00:33:26,037 --> 00:33:30,089
I think you're scared
that you've gone soft.

534
00:33:30,191 --> 00:33:33,109
You blame this hospital's
decline on it. Know what I think?

535
00:33:33,211 --> 00:33:36,212
- You're gonna tell me.
- It's not doing
you one bit of good!

536
00:33:36,314 --> 00:33:38,114
Surgeons are
dropping like dominoes.

537
00:33:38,216 --> 00:33:41,268
So, maybe it's time you got in
touch with your feminine side.

538
00:33:41,370 --> 00:33:44,087
Maybe you need a little soft.

539
00:33:47,792 --> 00:33:50,376
You still shouldn't
have ratted me out.

540
00:33:50,478 --> 00:33:54,731
- Sorry.
- Me, too.

541
00:34:02,924 --> 00:34:04,056
What are you doing?

542
00:34:04,158 --> 00:34:06,476
Assigning myself to
trauma with you tomorrow.

543
00:34:06,578 --> 00:34:10,080
I'm a big girl. I can
handle my share of trauma.

544
00:34:10,182 --> 00:34:12,732
And I get to decide
when I've had enough.

545
00:34:15,020 --> 00:34:19,071
It's gonna take a lot more than
a bad dream to scare me off.

546
00:34:21,442 --> 00:34:23,709
It is more than a bad dream.

547
00:34:25,830 --> 00:34:26,946
I know.

548
00:34:34,489 --> 00:34:38,525
<i>♪ Didn't know that
they were dying ♪</i>

549
00:34:40,696 --> 00:34:43,329
<i>♪ You varnished
all the leaves... ♪</i>

550
00:34:43,431 --> 00:34:47,934
I know I have no business
asking you for anything,

551
00:34:48,036 --> 00:34:49,569
but I need your help.

552
00:34:49,671 --> 00:34:51,838
I need you to bring Derek back.

553
00:34:54,893 --> 00:34:57,327
And he's not "fine."

554
00:34:59,831 --> 00:35:03,200
Sometimes people
just want to be left alone.

555
00:35:15,647 --> 00:35:18,932
He's planning to propose.

556
00:35:19,034 --> 00:35:23,036
He's been carrying
around a big ring for weeks.

557
00:35:23,138 --> 00:35:26,172
That's not a man who
wants to be left alone.

558
00:35:31,813 --> 00:35:34,480
I just thought you should know.

559
00:35:36,618 --> 00:35:39,919
<i>♪ With a tin of creosole ♪</i>

560
00:35:43,057 --> 00:35:46,710
<i>♪ What on earth... ♪</i>

561
00:35:48,363 --> 00:35:51,731
Yes, the odds are against us.
I'm a one woman wrecking ball.

562
00:35:51,833 --> 00:35:55,685
All I do is break you. Your hand,
penis, relationships, your life...

563
00:35:55,787 --> 00:36:00,806
I'd say our survival rate is about
three percent. And that's bad.

564
00:36:00,908 --> 00:36:02,776
But it's not nothing.

565
00:36:02,878 --> 00:36:05,896
I don't think we should
give up on this. Not yet...

566
00:36:06,698 --> 00:36:07,914
OK.

567
00:36:09,334 --> 00:36:11,454
You think you broke
me, Little Grey?

568
00:36:12,404 --> 00:36:15,572
You're the one who
put me back together.

569
00:36:21,947 --> 00:36:24,447
- Hand.
- Hand.

570
00:36:24,549 --> 00:36:28,684
Mark. I've got a couple of
Shepherd's post-ops to check in on,

571
00:36:28,786 --> 00:36:32,421
- but after that,
feel like a drink?
- How about a rain check, John?

572
00:36:33,258 --> 00:36:35,325
Jim.

573
00:36:35,994 --> 00:36:38,527
It's Jim.

574
00:36:47,355 --> 00:36:51,791
So I've had quite a day. Got my
ass handed to me by Alex Karev.

575
00:36:51,893 --> 00:36:55,679
A second year resident.
Which is humbling for a surgeon,

576
00:36:55,780 --> 00:37:00,082
- especially a know-it-all...
- We don't have to do this,
be friends.

577
00:37:00,184 --> 00:37:03,236
It's a big hospital, lots of
floors, lots of places to hide.

578
00:37:03,338 --> 00:37:05,889
I'm perfectly OK with doing
that for the next few years.

579
00:37:05,990 --> 00:37:08,307
You're not hearing me, Calliope.

580
00:37:08,409 --> 00:37:11,261
Sometimes I panic in
the moment, I call it wrong.

581
00:37:11,363 --> 00:37:13,446
I misjudge a situation.

582
00:37:13,548 --> 00:37:18,134
So if you're up for it, I'd
like to take you to dinner.

583
00:37:22,623 --> 00:37:24,223
Maybe.

584
00:37:25,109 --> 00:37:26,376
Maybe?

585
00:37:26,478 --> 00:37:28,961
My schedule's kind of
insane right now, so...

586
00:37:29,064 --> 00:37:30,846
I'll get back to you.

587
00:37:35,153 --> 00:37:37,437
How's, uh, tomorrow?

588
00:37:43,628 --> 00:37:45,995
<i>♪ Black crows
circling up above ♪</i>

589
00:37:46,098 --> 00:37:50,199
<i>♪ Crying out "Do you
hear that sound?" ♪</i>

590
00:37:50,302 --> 00:37:52,502
<i>♪ I'd never thought
it'd come to this... ♪</i>

591
00:37:52,604 --> 00:37:54,871
- Good night, Iz.
- Night.

592
00:37:59,344 --> 00:38:00,744
Um...

593
00:38:00,845 --> 00:38:03,296
I've been keeping my
distance 'cause you're with Alex.

594
00:38:03,398 --> 00:38:08,067
I just want to let you know
I'm still here. I still care.

595
00:38:09,604 --> 00:38:10,636
Thanks, George.

596
00:38:10,739 --> 00:38:12,859
And you don't
want to talk about it?

597
00:38:12,940 --> 00:38:14,807
Not yet.

598
00:38:15,810 --> 00:38:18,961
- OK. Good night.
- Night.

599
00:38:23,067 --> 00:38:26,569
<i>♪ Some are blind
but choose to see ♪</i>

600
00:38:26,671 --> 00:38:29,472
<i>♪ Lies into the truth... ♪</i>

601
00:38:29,574 --> 00:38:32,014
You don't like me
very much, do you?

602
00:38:32,109 --> 00:38:34,177
- Uh...
- No. That's good.

603
00:38:34,279 --> 00:38:36,979
It's good. Because I
need to tell you something.

604
00:38:37,065 --> 00:38:43,086
I need to tell you because I need to
tell somebody and... you're a robot.

605
00:38:43,754 --> 00:38:45,621
You can take it.

606
00:38:46,391 --> 00:38:47,891
OK.

607
00:38:49,695 --> 00:38:52,946
- I can't tell you here.
- OK.

608
00:38:53,048 --> 00:38:56,782
- I can't...
- OK.

609
00:38:58,537 --> 00:39:00,503
OK.

